	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: The best nes asm compiler?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I don't like the NESASM way to use zero-page addressing, but at least it's optional. ASM6, AFAIK, always uses zero-page instructions when accessing memory at $0000-$00FF. This bothers me a bit when I'm coding Atari 2600 programs, which often need precisely timed code to render the screen. Without a way to force absolute addressing, I must either write instructions with .db statements or use a mirror of $0000-$00FF instead.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
